<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1478,1945]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,288,1478,1504]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41">Female</emphasis>
. Similar to male except for usual, slight dimorphism. 
<emphasis box="[936,1155,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="41">Female terminalia</emphasis>
(fig. 
<number box="[1223,1256,1479,1505]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" value="10.0">10</number>
). Postabdomen with cerci abruptly oriented forwardly, their ventral sides being just below hypoproct; outline of cercus distinctly sharp, with strong, blunt, apical, spinelike seta; sternite 
<number box="[904,919,1559,1585]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" value="8.0">8</number>
with two median, elongated sclerites, each bearing 
<number box="[246,260,1599,1625]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" value="2.0">2</number>
stout setae; hypoproct microscopically setulose, strongly curved towards sternite 
<number box="[1220,1234,1599,1625]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" value="8.0">8</number>
(fig. 
<number box="[1299,1332,1599,1625]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" value="10.0">10</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
